Let $T$ be the set of all teams, and note that $\frac 1{\binom{n}{9}}\sum_{A\subset [n],|A|=9}\left|A\cap T\right|$ is just the average size of the number of teams that some 9 people have in common. The problem states that this averages $\frac 1{\binom{n}{8}}\sum_{A\subset [n],|A|=8}\left|A\cap T\right|$ over all possible teams. Expand binomial coefficients to get \begin{align*}\frac 1{\binom{n}{9}}\sum_{A\subset [n],|A|=9}\left|A\cap T\right|&=\frac 1n\sum_{x\in [n]}\sum_{\substack{A\subset [n],|A|=8\\x\in A}}\left|A\cap T\right|\\&=\frac 1n\sum_{x\in [n]}\sum_{Y\subset [n]\setminus\{x\},|Y|=7}\left|Y\cup\{x\}\cap T\right|\\&=\frac 1n\left(\sum_{Y\subset [n],|Y|=7}\left|Y\cap T\right|+\sum_{x\in [n]} \sum_{\substack{Y\subset [n],|Y|=7\\x\notin Y}}\left|Y\cap T\right|\right)\end{align*} \begin{align*}=\frac 1n\left(|T|+\sum_{x\in [n]}\left(8|T_x|\right)\right)\end{align*} where $T_x=\{t\in T:x\in t\}$. In addition, \begin{align*}\frac 1{\binom{n}{8}}\sum_{A\subset [n],|A|=8}\left|A\cap T\right|&=\frac 1n\sum_{x\in [n]}\frac{8|T_x|}9\\&=\frac 8n\left(\frac{|T|}9+\sum_{x\in [n]}\frac{|T_x|}9\right)\end{align*} For these averages to be equal, we must have $$|T|+\sum_{x\in [n]}8\left|\left(x,T_x\right)\right|=8|T|+64|T_x|$$ or, equivalently, \begin{align*}&\sum_{x\in [n]}8\left|\left(x,T_x\right)\right|=7|T|+64|T_x|\\ \implies & \frac{|T|}{|T_x|}=\frac{8}{7}\end{align*}By the Cauchy-Schwarz Inequality, \begin{align*}\left(\frac{|T|}{|T_x|}\right)^2&=\left(\frac{\sum_{x\in[n]}|T_x|}{|T_x|}\right)^2\le\frac{\sum_{x\in [n]}|T_x|}9\sum_{x\in [n]}\frac{|T_x|}{|T_x|}\\ &\implies \frac{|T|}{|T_x|}\le\frac{8}{7}\end{align*} with equality if and only if $T_x$ is constant. Therefore, $\left|\left(x, T_x\right)\right|=9$ for all $x\in [n]$. $\therefore n=9, 10,\cdots, 17,\, 20$. There is a total of $19-9+1=\boxed{\textbf{(A)}\,477}$.

